testCases.steps:
1. Open the page and review the available content.
2. Override the CSS on the page using a user stylesheet, bookmarklet, extension, or application with the values listed in the success criterion:
 a. Line height to at least 1.5 times the font size;
 b. Spacing following paragraphs to at least 2 times the font size;
 c. Letter spacing (tracking) to at least 0.12 times the font size;
 d. Word spacing to 0.16 times the font size.
3. Check if any content is clipped, obscured, or lost due to the new text spacing.

1. Identify the website's content pages (excluding checkout processes, multi-step forms, or sequential workflows).
2. Check for at least two of the following location methods exist:
- Site-wide navigation menu or links;
- Search functionality;
- Site map;
- Table of contents;
- Category/topic-based browsing;
- Alphabetical index;
- Related links or "you might also like" sections.
3. Test each identified method by locating the same target page using different approaches. Verify that both methods successfully lead to the intended page.

1. Check for location indicators such as:
- Breadcrumb navigation showing the path from home page to current page;
- Site maps highlighting the current page location;
- Navigation menus with current page highlighted or marked;
- Page titles that indicate position within site structure;
- URL structure that reflects site organization;
- "You are here" indicators.
2. Verify that location information is consistent across different pages. Check that location information is programmatically available (not just visual styling).

1. Use keyboard navigation to move focus through all interactive elements on the page (links, buttons, form controls, custom components). 
2. For each focused element, check that the entire component remains visible and is not hidden or covered by:
- Sticky headers or navigation bars;
- Fixed positioned elements (sidebars, toolbars, chat widgets);
- Modal dialogs or overlays;
- Dropdown menus from other components;
- Pop-up content or tooltips;
- Other floating or positioned content.
3. Test focus visibility at different viewport sizes and zoom levels (up to 200%).
4. Verify that focus indicators (focus rings, outlines, highlighting) are fully visible and not clipped.
5. Check that any content that moves or repositions when focus changes does not obscure the focused element.
6. Test with common browser zoom levels to ensure focus remains visible when content is enlarged and all focused UI components remain completely visible and unobscured by any author-created content.

testCases.description:
The size of the target for pointer inputs is at least 44 by 44 CSS pixels except when:
- Equivalent: The target is available through an equivalent link or control on the same page that is at least 44 by 44 CSS pixels;
- Inline: The target is in a sentence or block of text;
- User Agent Control: The size of the target is determined by the user agent and is not modified by the author;
- Essential: A particular presentation of the target is essential to the information being conveyed.

The size of the target for pointer inputs is at least 24 by 24 CSS pixels, except when: 
- Spacing: Undersized targets (those less than 24 by 24 CSS pixels) are positioned so that if a 24 CSS pixel diameter circle is centered on the bounding box of each, the circles do not intersect another target or the circle for another undersized target;
- Equivalent: The function can be achieved through a different control on the same page that meets this criterion;
- Inline: The target is in a sentence or its size is otherwise constrained by the line-height of non-target text;
- UA Control: The size of the target is determined by the user agent and is not modified by the author;
- Essential: A particular presentation of the target is essential or is legally required for the information being conveyed.
Note 1: Targets that allow for values to be selected spatially based on position within the target are considered one target for the purpose of the success criterion. Examples include sliders, color pickers displaying a gradient of colors, or editable areas where you position the cursor.
Note 2: For inline targets the line-height should be interpreted as perpendicular to the flow of text. For example, in a language displayed vertically, the line-height would be horizontal.

testCases.steps:
1. Identify the page's default language from the lang attribute on the <html> element.
2. Scan the page content for passages or phrases in different languages than the default.
3. Check that foreign language content has appropriate language markup using the lang attribute (e.g., <span lang="fr">Bonjour</span> for French text on an English page).
4. Verify that the following exceptions are correctly handled and do NOT require language markup:
- Proper names: Person names, place names, company names (e.g., "Jos", "Mnchen", "Toyota");
- Technical terms: Industry jargon, scientific terms, specialized vocabulary commonly used without translation;
- Indeterminate language: Words where the language cannot be reasonably determined;
- Vernacular adoption: Foreign words/phrases commonly used in the surrounding text's language (e.g., "caf" in English text);
- Test with screen reader software or browser language detection tools to confirm that language changes are properly announced;
- Verify that language codes used are valid (ISO 639-1 or BCP 47 standards).
5. All passages and phrases in languages different from the page default have appropriate language markup, except for properly identified exceptions.

1. Scan the page content for words or phrases that are used in unusual or restricted ways, including:
- Technical jargon specific to an industry or field;
- Idioms or colloquial expressions;
- Common words used with specialized meanings;
- Abbreviations or acronyms with specific contextual definitions;
- Terms that may be unfamiliar to general audiences.
2. Check for definition mechanisms, such as glossaries, inline definitions, etc.
3. Test that the definition mechanism is functional and accessible via keyboard navigation.
4. Verify that definitions are accurate and help clarify the unusual or restricted usage.
5. Confirm that the mechanism is consistently available throughout the site for similar specialized terms.

1. Assess the reading level of the page content.
2. Use readability assessment tools (Flesch-Kincaid, SMOG, or similar) to determine if the content exceeds lower secondary education level (approximately grade 9 or age 15).
3. If the content requires advanced reading ability, check for supplemental mechanisms, such as:
- Simplified version of the same content;
- Audio narration or video explanations;
- Visual aids like diagrams, charts, or illustrations;
- Glossaries defining complex terms;
- Executive summaries or key point highlights;
- Interactive tutorials or guided explanations.

1. Scan the page content for words that have multiple pronunciations with different meanings (e.g., homographs).
2. For ambiguous cases, check for pronunciation mechanisms, such as:
- Phonetic spelling or pronunciation guides in parentheses;
- Audio pronunciation clips activated by clicking or hovering;
- International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) notations;
- Ruby annotation showing pronunciation;
- Links to pronunciation resources or dictionaries;
- Stress marks or diacritical marks indicating pronunciation.

testCases.description:
If a web page contains any of the following help mechanisms, and those mechanisms are repeated on multiple web pages within a set of web pages, they occur in the same order relative to other page content, unless a change is initiated by the user:
- Human contact details;
- Human contact mechanism;
- Self-help option;
- A fully automated contact mechanism.
Note 1: Help mechanisms may be provided directly on the page, or may be provided via a direct link to a different page containing the information.
Note 2: For this success criterion, "the same order relative to other page content" can be thought of as how the content is ordered when the page is serialized. The visual position of a help mechanism is likely to be consistent across pages for the same page variation (e.g., CSS break-point). The user can initiate a change, such as changing the page's zoom or orientation, which may trigger a different page variation. This criterion is concerned with relative order across pages displayed in the same page variation (e.g., same zoom level and orientation).

For web pages that cause legal commitments or financial transactions for the user to occur, that modify or delete user-controllable data in data storage systems, or that submit user test responses, at least one of the following is true:
- Reversible: Submissions are reversible;
- Checked: Data entered by the user is checked for input errors and the user is provided an opportunity to correct them;
- Confirmed: A mechanism is available for reviewing, confirming, and correcting information before finalizing the submission.

For web pages that require the user to submit info, at least one of the following is true:
- Reversible: Submissions are reversible;
- Checked: Data entered by the user is checked for input errors and the user is provided an opportunity to correct them;
- Confirmed: A mechanism is available for reviewing, confirming, and correcting information before finalizing the submission.

